title: Perth council under fire for anti-homeless noise devices | 7NEWS
description: The City of Perth has installed high-pitched noise-emitting speakers in a CBD underpass and car parks, which rough sleepers say effectively prevents them from sheltering in these locations. Homelessness advocates have criticised the devices as hostile architecture, while the council maintains they are safety measures, with neither the City nor transport authority taking clear responsibility for the decision. The controversy follows a similar incident in Bunbury in 2023 where a Wiggles song was played on loop to deter homeless people. title: Thousands of Victorian healthcare workers set to strike
description: About 10,000 healthcare workers will be walking off the job on Wednesday amidst a pay dispute with the Victorian government.  The day-long strike is expected to disrupt operations at more than 80 health services, including all major Melbourne hospitals.  It comes two weeks after Health Workers Union (HWU) in Victoria rejected a three-year deal from the government.  The offer increases pay rates by 5 per cent for the next two years and would not see any change for the final year. #healthcare #strike #union #health #pay

title: UK police probe Andrew's Epstein flight log links | 7NEWS
description: UK police have launched a national investigation into Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor's connections to Jeffrey Epstein's flight logs, examining claims that young women were trafficked into Britain aboard Epstein's private jet. Investigators will analyse at least 90 flights from the aircraft known as the Lolita Express, including 15 flights that occurred after Epstein's conviction for soliciting underage sex. New unredacted emails have emerged stating as fact that Andrew had sex with Virginia Dufresne, despite years of denials and a reported $24 million out-of-court settlement, while British MPs consider whether a parliamentary probe into Andrew's conduct as UK trade envoy is necessary. title: Women's stroke symptoms often misdiagnosed | 7NEWS
description: Strokes kill more than twice as many Australian women per year than breast cancer, with new figures revealing a critical gap in diagnosis. Women are 25 per cent less likely than men to have their stroke symptoms recognised quickly. Atypical stroke symptoms in women, including nausea, confusion and headaches, are often misdiagnosed, leading experts to call for these warning signs to be taken more seriously.
